"This accusation is general, against all who would be thought heroic poets; but I think it touches Virgil less than any. He is too great a master of his art, to make a blot which may so easily be hit. Similitudes, as I have said, are not for tragedy, which is all violent, and where the passions are in a perpetual ferment ; for there they deaden where they should arimate; they are not of the nature of dialogue, unless in comedy : a metaphor is almost all the stage can suffer, whichis a kind of simili- tude comprehended in a word. But this figure has"